It sounded really fun.

27
00:02:03,954 --> 00:02:04,274
Yeah.

28
00:02:05,015 --> 00:02:05,615
So yeah.

29
00:02:05,815 --> 00:02:08,996
So we're here to talk mostly about your campaign for state Senate.

30
00:02:09,656 --> 00:02:21,621
Um, so I'm wondering if you could just tell us a little bit about kind of how you arrived at this moment to, to, to kind of shift tracks from state representative to, um, running for Senate state Senate.

31
00:02:22,867 --> 00:02:32,274
Yeah, so I've been state representative for my sixth term for Somerville and Medford and it's an amazing community and I really love that work and I've been honored to do it.

32
00:02:33,315 --> 00:02:36,838
It really goes back to though why I got into this work.

33
00:02:37,458 --> 00:02:44,684
The daughter of a public school teacher, my mom worked as a public school teacher and my dad worked in a manufacturing plant and they really taught me

34
00:02:45,304 --> 00:02:50,447
the values of women leading, of social justice, of workers' rights.

35
00:02:50,948 --> 00:02:58,332
And after college, I did a volunteer program and did community organizing working with low-income women.

36
00:02:58,532 --> 00:03:07,418
And it was after welfare reform, which really upended the lives of low-income women, and we did community organizing.

37
00:03:08,578 --> 00:03:17,345
and brought them to the state house where they could share their voices about what they really needed, which was child care, health care, training for good jobs.

38
00:03:18,046 --> 00:03:26,312
And that was a really formative experience for me of people who have the most urgent needs being able to share their voice to get really good policy made.

39
00:03:28,474 --> 00:03:36,160
And I eventually got into working on health care and especially Medicaid to expand access to health care and try to get to universal health care.

40
00:03:38,038 --> 00:03:48,081
And I worked on Massachusetts health reform as a legislative staffer and then as a advocate worked on the Affordable Care Act.

41
00:03:48,201 --> 00:03:59,544
So for most of my career, I've been working on policy and really making sure to listen to people who have kind of the most urgent needs and the most vulnerable to make sure that policy is working for them.

42
00:04:00,621 --> 00:04:08,147
So as state rep, that's the work I've done and been able to get a lot of results at the state house and excited for the district and the state Senate.

43
00:04:08,227 --> 00:04:25,319
It is all of Somerville, Medford, and includes Cambridge and Winchester, which are newer areas to me, but it's a district that is super civically engaged, wants things to be different, wants to look out for neighbors and make sure that everyone is safe.

44
00:04:26,280 --> 00:04:27,821
has what they need here.

45
00:04:28,321 --> 00:04:35,863
And I'm really excited about just working with residents to get even more done in the Senate and be able to organize and make that happen.

46
00:04:36,983 --> 00:04:48,627
Yeah, I'm wondering if you could talk a little bit about some of the things you've already gotten done as a state rep and kind of, you know, if there's any highlights for kind of what's helping you like move into maybe a bigger position here.

47
00:04:49,267 --> 00:04:52,449
Yeah, and I should also say it's not lost on me.

48
00:04:52,489 --> 00:04:56,091
So Senator Pat Jalen has done this work for decades at the State House.

49
00:04:56,131 --> 00:05:02,714
She's an incredible mentor of mine who I've been able to work with, but leaves impossibly big shoes to fill.

50
00:05:03,035 --> 00:05:05,656
And she's just been an amazing, effective leader.

51
00:05:05,736 --> 00:05:16,822
So I don't want to not mention what an incredible leader Pat is and that I feel really lucky to have worked with her for a number of years.

52
00:05:20,118 --> 00:05:24,723
So as I mentioned, I was a health care advocate before I ran for office.

53
00:05:25,124 --> 00:05:27,446
And health care is a right.

54
00:05:27,526 --> 00:05:28,508
And I really believe that.

55
00:05:28,568 --> 00:05:33,453
And I've spent a lot of my work opening up access to health care.

56
00:05:33,593 --> 00:05:39,019
So I passed a bill last year, which is a bill that I wrote to cap

57
00:05:40,257 --> 00:05:50,383
co-pays for insulin and for inhalers because people shouldn't have to choose between medication and groceries or paying the rent.

58
00:05:51,124 --> 00:06:03,992
And that was something that we were seeing, especially for communities of color and low-income families that insulin and inhalers are just things you need to stay healthy and should not be things where you're figuring out how to pay for them.

59
00:06:05,284 --> 00:06:10,765
I also passed a law to expand connector care, which is like subsidized healthcare under the ACA.

60
00:06:10,825 --> 00:06:16,126
So Massachusetts, we actually allow that to go up to 500% of the poverty level.

61
00:06:16,186 --> 00:06:19,087
So the more moderate income people can get subsidized care.

62
00:06:19,227 --> 00:06:22,908
And that was something that I worked on and that we got passed into law.

63
00:06:24,508 --> 00:06:34,550
I've worked on contraception access, access for transgender folks, and just making sure that people have access to all sorts of healthcare.

64
00:06:35,549 --> 00:06:36,649
That's one that I'm really proud of.

65
00:06:36,669 --> 00:06:42,552
I think maybe the last time we talked, you were working on something for IDs for undocumented folks.

66
00:06:43,072 --> 00:06:43,592
Yeah.

67
00:06:43,712 --> 00:06:44,072
Yeah.

68
00:06:44,152 --> 00:06:48,114
So one of my proudest accomplishments is the work and family mobility act.

69
00:06:48,294 --> 00:06:50,354
And yeah, I think we did that on an earlier episode.

70
00:06:50,374 --> 00:06:50,675
So that.

71
00:06:52,054 --> 00:06:56,616
bill people organized for about 17 years to get it passed.

72
00:06:57,096 --> 00:07:06,560
And I worked on it because local residents here in Medford and Somerville asked me to take it up as a key priority for immigrant communities.

73
00:07:07,061 --> 00:07:12,043
And that bill allows people to get a driver's license regardless of their immigration status.

74
00:07:13,744 --> 00:07:15,644
And so we fought really hard.

75
00:07:15,704 --> 00:07:20,887
We had an amazing coalition across the state and I worked

76
00:07:21,787 --> 00:07:24,488
with my legislative colleagues to build support.

77
00:07:24,568 --> 00:07:28,830
And it was actually really hard to build support at the time for that bill.

78
00:07:28,870 --> 00:07:33,372
But it took us about three and a half years, and we did get it passed.

79
00:07:34,673 --> 00:07:37,534
And we had to withstand a veto by then Governor Baker.

80
00:07:38,934 --> 00:07:41,075
But we were able to get that law passed.

81
00:07:41,175 --> 00:07:48,999
And now tens of thousands of people have driver's licenses, and it keeps them safe so they're not stopped for driving without a license.

82
00:07:49,399 --> 00:07:50,840
And it actually helps now.

83
00:07:52,051 --> 00:08:05,862
with all the challenges with ICE is that it's one way to keep people safe because they have a license, they can get to work, they can take their kid to school and not have to worry about that of not driving without a license as one piece of it.

84
00:08:07,884 --> 00:08:09,925
So working with that coalition has been really incredible.

85
00:08:09,945 --> 00:08:16,410
Yeah, it seems like you've had like a pretty good reach and had like a lot of influence already as a state rep.

86
00:08:16,450 --> 00:08:20,794
I wonder like, what do you see as different about the role of a state senator?

87
00:08:22,055 --> 00:08:27,537
Yeah, so one of the things that I've been able to do well is get things passed and get money for the district.

88
00:08:27,857 --> 00:08:45,342
And it is harder, some would say harder than it should be to do that in Massachusetts, but I've been successful in building coalitions, both working with advocates on the ground, grassroots advocates, because that's always really important on issues to have the voice of people who are most affected.

89
00:08:46,182 --> 00:08:54,567
And then working with my legislative colleagues and working with people who have different experiences in different districts, but to get them on board.

90
00:08:54,667 --> 00:08:56,969
And we definitely did that with the driver's license bill.

91
00:08:57,649 --> 00:08:58,970
I've been doing that with a bill.

92
00:08:58,990 --> 00:09:05,294
I filed this session to stop ICE from deputizing our local and state law enforcement.

93
00:09:06,094 --> 00:09:15,123
And I worked really closely with the Black and Latino caucus to get that into a bill, the PROTECT Act that we passed a couple weeks ago in the House and the Senate just passed.

94
00:09:15,704 --> 00:09:21,530
So it's a lot of coalition building and organizing inside the statehouse.

95
00:09:23,251 --> 00:09:25,052
In the Senate, there are fewer people.

96
00:09:25,232 --> 00:09:35,118
There's 40 senators and there are progressive senators who have a few progressive senators who have been elected recently.

97
00:09:35,298 --> 00:09:48,826
And I'm really excited about leading in the Senate and getting more done and being able to organize to get progressive legislation really on the agenda and get more passed and get the results that we urgently need right now.

98
00:09:49,646 --> 00:09:57,372
Yeah, and it's a big geographical area, a lot of people that this different district would cover.

99
00:09:57,412 --> 00:10:01,335
And it's pretty diverse, I would say, or I would imagine.

100
00:10:02,877 --> 00:10:06,860
So it seems like a big job and a lot of people to try to please, yeah.

101
00:10:07,827 --> 00:10:34,535
Yeah, and we've been, I've been canvassing a lot all around the district, which is, so going door to door is honestly one of my favorite parts of the job and the best way to get to know it, because having one-on-one conversations with people and seeing some of the different neighborhoods, you get a sense of what's going on for them, what their concerns are, and that's really the best way to get a sense of, especially the newer areas for me to represent.

102
00:10:35,175 --> 00:10:37,276
And to some extent, you hear the same thing.

103
00:10:37,316 --> 00:10:49,021
I'm hearing a lot about people scared about immigration and just wanting to stand up for neighbors, people frustrated about affordability, cost of health care, cost of housing.

104
00:10:52,650 --> 00:10:56,173
and just wanting something different than what's going on.

105
00:10:56,193 --> 00:11:05,559
And I've been able to talk about, okay, well, I've gotten results and I have a track record and I would love to work with you on these pieces.

106
00:11:05,579 --> 00:11:18,108
Yeah, I think you've spoken like kind of maybe to this in a way, but I wonder if how you think about like yourself as maybe different or set apart from the other folks that are running for the same seat.

107
00:11:18,849 --> 00:11:19,629
Yeah, so,

108
00:11:21,273 --> 00:11:24,494
There are five of us running, it's a democratic primary.

109
00:11:24,714 --> 00:11:28,034
So all of us running, there's five people running in the democratic primary.

110
00:11:29,234 --> 00:11:32,175
And we're all pretty progressive, we all share progressive values.

111
00:11:32,555 --> 00:11:35,296
But what sets me apart is that I've really delivered results.

112
00:11:36,216 --> 00:11:42,357
And for me, progressive leadership isn't just about promising things or having progressive ideas.

113
00:11:42,537 --> 00:11:47,838
It is about delivering results for people, especially when there's really urgent needs right now.

114
00:11:48,938 --> 00:11:58,327
And so I have done that in working with immigrants and working on housing and health care, work on climate and delivering a lot of money to the district too.

115
00:11:58,487 --> 00:12:09,577
So I helped to get money to bring the Green Line extension a number of years ago, which has been really transformative to Somerville and to the neighborhoods of Medford that I represent.

116
00:12:10,482 --> 00:12:20,633
Um, money for, um, things like the mystic community market, which is the big food bank in my district and to the wise and other early education programs.

117
00:12:21,494 --> 00:12:29,262
Um, and to many of the parks, um, like McDonald park and riverbed park along the mystic river and really keeping those up.

118
00:12:30,136 --> 00:12:34,358
Um, and then delivering for our schools, which is also one of the top things I hear on the doors.

119
00:12:35,178 --> 00:12:55,106
Um, I was able to get money in the budget this year to support, um, some of the career technical education programs at Medford high, which are incredible programs that students are really, um, asking for and, um, making sure that they have enough opportunity to, to be able to build out those programs and really support the students there.

120
00:12:55,126 --> 00:12:57,588
Great.

121
00:12:57,648 --> 00:12:57,808
Yeah.

122
00:12:57,828 --> 00:12:58,608
It sounds like a lot of,

123
00:12:59,092 --> 00:13:20,086
already great relationship building connections to folks and like seeing these things in action and when you were talking about the licenses for undocumented folks that was a very long process and I think sometimes people politicians can lose sight of like these things that are really important because they take so long and like something new and exciting will come up but so it sounds like you have

124
00:13:20,646 --> 00:13:23,569
a lot of, you know, dedication to these really important causes.

125
00:13:24,710 --> 00:13:33,699
One of the, and I think one of the new things that, or maybe, I don't know how new this is, but one of the things that we're hearing from you now is about this cell phone bill for students, right?

126
00:13:33,719 --> 00:13:36,062
So could you talk us through that one a little bit?

127
00:13:37,043 --> 00:13:46,265
Yeah, so this is something that I've been hearing about from parents and teachers for a while is the challenge of cell phones in schools.

128
00:13:47,505 --> 00:13:59,467
And so we passed in the house a bell to bell cell phone ban in public schools that included also a social media prohibition for children under 14.

129
00:14:00,207 --> 00:14:05,068
And we've all seen the studies about mental health and young people and what social media

130
00:14:06,288 --> 00:14:12,471
and cell phone use is doing to their brains and to their social emotional learning.

131
00:14:13,412 --> 00:14:23,677
We know that there's algorithms that are specifically built for addictive design and to exploit young people and all of us, but especially young developing minds.

132
00:14:25,258 --> 00:14:33,262
So the Mass Teachers Association and many of the groups we worked with on this bill really support the bell to bell

133
00:14:35,631 --> 00:14:43,756
So basically, schools will allow for a way so parents can reach their child.

134
00:14:43,896 --> 00:15:01,027
And if a child, of course, has health issues or other things, that there'll be ways that they can address communicating, but making sure that children are in school to learn and to really focus and not to be on their phones and distracted in that way.

135
00:15:02,161 --> 00:15:05,684
And I'm curious if there's been any resistance to this idea.

136
00:15:06,344 --> 00:15:07,125
Yeah.

137
00:15:07,225 --> 00:15:14,750
I've definitely heard some resistance and some parents who want their kids to have cell phones in schools.

138
00:15:14,930 --> 00:15:16,191
And I hear that.

139
00:15:18,633 --> 00:15:22,075
And it's not taking away, of course, young people's cell phones.

140
00:15:22,096 --> 00:15:25,778
It's just when they're in the school day, they would not have them during that time.

141
00:15:27,860 --> 00:15:29,221
The social media ban.

142
00:15:32,038 --> 00:15:43,425
To be clear, when we pass that, there is no specific way cited for how you'll verify age, and that has been one of the things that's come up.

143
00:15:43,966 --> 00:15:51,831
So we asked the Attorney General to come up with, through a public process, how to verify age, because that is a challenging piece.

144
00:15:52,722 --> 00:16:14,469
Um, and I did work with the LGBT caucus on the House floor on an amendment to protect LGBT kids who want to, you know, who do use social media sometimes as a lifeline when they're not in a, when they're in a perhaps unsafe or, um, situation where there isn't other support and, um,

145
00:16:15,230 --> 00:16:18,671
trying to make sure that we're supporting all kids in addressing this.

146
00:16:20,412 --> 00:16:22,673
And I would just say, this is the House version.

147
00:16:22,753 --> 00:16:23,953
So the bill is not final.

148
00:16:24,373 --> 00:16:31,336
And as I continue to hear from constituents about some concerns, I'm working on the Senate side too.

149
00:16:31,436 --> 00:16:33,797
So in the final version, we can try to get this right.

150
00:16:34,817 --> 00:16:38,759
We're also working on a big data privacy bill, which includes

151
00:16:39,659 --> 00:16:41,140
not just young people, but all of us.

152
00:16:42,400 --> 00:16:44,921
So that will also come into play on this.

153
00:16:45,181 --> 00:16:47,582
And we're looking at things like location shields.

154
00:16:47,622 --> 00:17:00,747
So if you're getting health care access, health care services, especially if you're getting reproductive care or gender affirming care, that these apps and things that track us everywhere will have more settings.

155
00:17:00,847 --> 00:17:04,888
So we're also looking more broadly at data privacy in this whole debate.

156
00:17:05,718 --> 00:17:07,079
Oh, cool.

157
00:17:07,159 --> 00:17:07,860
It's really interesting.

158
00:17:09,201 --> 00:17:15,185
So before we kind of wrap up, I'm wondering if you have if there's anything else that we haven't talked about that you think is important for folks to know.

159
00:17:18,548 --> 00:17:20,549
Yeah, so I really appreciate the time.

160
00:17:20,669 --> 00:17:34,237
And what I would say is it's an urgent time where so many people are under attack in our communities, both by the federal government and by just the challenges that we have with affordability.

161
00:17:35,117 --> 00:17:39,880
And in talking to people around the district, I'm hearing a real need for

162
00:17:41,060 --> 00:18:01,451
urgent solutions, and I have the record where I have been able to pass things to do that, and I want to, in the Senate, be able to pass bills, get more money, and make sure that I'm delivering, and that's what I've done in the House, and have the record to show that I can do that in the Senate as well.

163
00:18:02,633 --> 00:18:17,439
Um, and I would just say, you know, as we go forward, I hope to hear from more people, um, about what they're concerned about and talk about, like, let's, let's make some changes and what can we do at the state level to address, um, so many of these things.

164
00:18:17,539 --> 00:18:24,002
I think that's something people don't know that at the state level, we do a lot of work on education and healthcare and things that impact our everyday lives.

165
00:18:24,082 --> 00:18:26,483
And I definitely want to work with, with folks on that.

166
00:18:27,103 --> 00:18:27,363
Yeah.

167
00:18:27,383 --> 00:18:30,845
I think like we, with everything that's happening in the world, that's like really awful.

168
00:18:32,164 --> 00:18:36,187
think a lot of people, you know, I hear a lot of people say like, Oh, well, at least we live in Massachusetts.

169
00:18:36,247 --> 00:18:50,757
And like, I, it's, I don't know, I think that's kind of dismissive of all the work that has to be like constantly done to make sure that like, we stay that like, you know, we like kind of maintain our progressive values and that we keep some of those like,

170
00:18:51,840 --> 00:18:55,384
policies and laws that are important to protecting everybody.

171
00:18:56,425 --> 00:18:57,286
Yeah, absolutely.

172
00:18:57,326 --> 00:18:59,308
I mean, I do think we're the last line of defense.

173
00:19:00,409 --> 00:19:04,613
And I take that really seriously, that the state needs to stand up and protect people here.

174
00:19:05,274 --> 00:19:07,116
And that means we have to pass things.

175
00:19:07,156 --> 00:19:13,202
So we passed the Roe Act and the Shield 2.0 Act to make sure we're enshrining

176
00:19:14,423 --> 00:19:17,706
abortion care, reproductive care, and gender-affirming care in our state law.

177
00:19:17,787 --> 00:19:22,411
So as the feds are rolling back those protections, we're standing up.

178
00:19:23,672 --> 00:19:32,201
I've done some work to make sure we're holding on to all of our health care access and funds for health care because that has also been rolled back at the federal level.

179
00:19:32,461 --> 00:19:37,766
And then supporting immigrants and making sure those are things we're doing at the state level to stand up for our neighbors.

180
00:19:38,978 --> 00:19:49,764
But yes, there is work that we need to continue to do and get past here to actually put that into law and make it real for people on the ground.

181
00:19:49,784 --> 00:19:51,425
Well, thank you.

182
00:19:52,265 --> 00:19:58,208
Any events coming up that people can meet with you at or ways to give feedback or get involved in your campaign?

183
00:19:58,729 --> 00:19:59,169
Yeah.

184
00:19:59,269 --> 00:20:04,872
So I'm actually having an event at Tamper in Medford Hillside on June 2nd.

185
00:20:07,073 --> 00:20:09,415
5 to 7 p.m., so come.

186
00:20:09,695 --> 00:20:18,002
You can hear about the campaign, get involved, or if you're just interested, I would love to chat with you and meet people there.

187
00:20:18,862 --> 00:20:22,745
My website is christinebarber.org.

188
00:20:24,006 --> 00:20:32,213
I'm easy to find on Instagram and Facebook, and there's ways on my website and other platforms to email me, call me.

